    <exercise id="fs-id1346384" type="problem-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2664735">    <para id="import-auto-id2719096">Find the velocity of a proton that has a momentum of <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>4</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>48</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>–10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">-</m:mo><m:mtext>19</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext> kg⋅m/s</m:mtext><m:mtext>.</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math></para></problem></exercise>
    <exercise id="fs-id1298007" type="problem-exercises"><problem id="fs-id3433592">    <para id="import-auto-id2559859">(a) Calculate the speed of a <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>1.00-</m:mn><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mtext>g</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:math> particle of dust that has the same momentum as a proton moving at <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>0</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>999</m:mtext><m:mi>c</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>. (b) What does the small speed tell us about the mass of a proton compared to even a tiny amount of macroscopic matter?</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id1573484">
    <para id="import-auto-id704531">(a) <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>121</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>–8</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext> m/s</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math></para><para id="import-auto-id1677815">(b) The small speed tells us that the mass of a proton is substantially smaller than that of even a tiny amount of macroscopic matter!</para>
    </solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise id="fs-id1949487" type="problem-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1351776">    <para id="import-auto-id2719508">(a) Calculate <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>γ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> for a proton that has a momentum of <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>1.00 kg⋅m/s</m:mtext><m:mtext>.</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> (b) What is its speed? Such protons form a rare component of cosmic radiation with uncertain origins.</para></problem></exercise>
